# Rails HMVC Architecture Rules

## 1. Directory Structure Rules

### 1.1 Component Organization
- All components must be organized under appropriate namespaced directories (e.g., `v1/`)
- Controllers must be placed in `app/controllers/{version}/`
- Operations must be placed in `app/operations/{version}/{resource}/`
- Forms must be placed in `app/forms/{version}/{resource}/`
- Serializers must be placed in `app/serializers/{version}/`
- Models must be placed in `app/models/`
- Errors must be placed in `lib/errors/`

### 1.2 File Size Limits
- Individual files should not exceed 300 lines of code
- If a file grows beyond this limit, it should be refactored into smaller, focused components

## 2. Component Rules

### 2.1 Controller Rules
- Controllers must inherit from `ApplicationController` or its versioned variants
- Controllers should only handle HTTP requests and responses
- Business logic must be delegated to Operations
- Controllers must use the Renderable and Errorable concerns
- Controllers must not contain direct database calls
- Controllers must use wrap_parameters false

### 2.2 Form Rules
- Forms must inherit from `ApplicationForm`
- Forms must include ActiveModel::Model and ActiveModel::Attributes
- Forms must only handle parameter validation and data transformation
- Forms must not interact directly with the database
- Forms must implement valid! method for validation
- Forms must provide clear error messages

### 2.3 Operation Rules
- Operations must inherit from `ApplicationOperation`
- Operations must expose only a public `call` interface
- Complex business logic must be broken down into private `step_` methods
- Operations must handle all business logic and database interactions
- Operations must receive params and context data through initialization

### 2.4 Serializer Rules
- Serializers must inherit from `ApplicationSerializer`
- Serializers must handle only response formatting
- Serializers must not contain business logic
- Serializers must follow consistent naming conventions

### 2.5 Error Handling Rules
- Custom errors must inherit from appropriate base error classes
- Error responses must follow standardized JSON format
- Error handling must be implemented through the Errorable concern
- Resource-specific errors must use ResourceError class

## 3. Code Quality Rules

### 3.1 General Practices
- Follow Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- Maintain clear separation of concerns
- Use meaningful and consistent naming conventions
- Avoid code duplication
- Write self-documenting code
- Include appropriate comments for complex logic

### 3.2 Testing Requirements
- All components must have corresponding test files
- Tests must cover both success and failure scenarios
- Controllers must have request specs
- Operations must have unit tests
- Forms must have validation specs
- Models must have unit and integration tests

## 4. Configuration Rules

### 4.1 YAML Configuration
- Project configuration must be defined in `rails_hmvc.yml`
- Configuration must specify project type (api/web)
- Parent classes must be defined in configuration
- Version namespaces must be declared in configuration

### 4.2 Environment Handling
- Environment-specific code must be properly segregated
- No stubbing or fake data patterns in development or production
- Test environment may use mocked data
- Environment variables must be properly managed through .env files

## 5. API Design Rules

### 5.1 Versioning
- All API endpoints must be versioned
- Version must be included in URL path
- Breaking changes must trigger version increment

### 5.2 Response Format
- Responses must follow consistent JSON structure
- Error responses must include appropriate HTTP status codes
- Success responses must include appropriate metadata
- Pagination must be implemented where applicable

## 6. Security Rules

### 6.1 General Security
- No sensitive data in logs or error messages
- Proper authentication and authorization checks
- No hardcoded credentials or API keys
- Use of environment variables for sensitive data

### 6.2 Input Validation
- All user input must be validated
- Form objects must handle input sanitization
- Proper error handling for invalid input
- Protection against common security vulnerabilities
